For Alice’s expired JWT, keep the same principal and refresh in place.

- Detect expiry via `db.onAuthChanged(...)` or `db.getAuthState()` (check `error: "expired"`).
- Keep the same `Db`/`JazzProvider` instance and call `db.updateAuthToken(freshAliceJwt)` only when `sub` is the same Alice user id.
- Do not call `db.updateAuthToken(null)` for sign-out.

Then for switching to Bob:
- Fully sign out/clear Alice at the identity provider level first.
- Replace the client when principal changes (do **not** mutate in place with `updateAuthToken(null)`).
- Recreate from scratch with Bob’s token and new provider keys.

```ts
const aliceState = await db.getAuthState();
if (aliceState.error === "expired") {
  await db.updateAuthToken(freshAliceJwt);
}

await db.logout(); // stop Alice client
await provider.logout();

const bobDb = await createDb({ appId, serverUrl, jwtToken: bobJwt });
```

If using cookie-backed auth, replace `cookieSession`/provider instance entirely for Bob rather than trying to patch the old session.

Set up one singleton Node backend context in a server-only module, with a persistent driver and explicit shutdown:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  app,
  permissions,
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET!,
  driver: {
    type: "persistent",
    dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data",
  },
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});

process.on("SIGINT", async () => {
  await jazz.shutdown();
  process.exit(0);
});
```

Key constraints:
- Create the context once (module singleton), never per request.
- Use `persistent` driver for durable local Node storage; keep `dataPath` stable across restarts.
- `memory` driver is ephemeral and requires `serverUrl` to an upstream server for durability.
- Install `jazz-napi` for Node use.
- `BACKEND_SECRET` is required for `asBackend()/forRequest/forSession/withAttribution*` scopes.
- Keep `BACKEND_SECRET` and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` server-only (never exposed in public env).
- For endpoints that promise server-visible success, wait explicit durability tier as needed (for example edge confirmation for server-facing writes).
- In hot-reload/dev setups, preserve singleton lifecycle and ensure proper `shutdown` on exit.

Pass a query factory so updates are tracked when inputs change.

**Svelte**
```ts
import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
import { app } from "./schema";

const db = getDb();
const [filter, setFilter] = $state("");

const todosSub = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  filter() ? app.todos.where({ title: { contains: filter() } }) : app.todos
);

// render using todosSub.current, todosSub.loading, todosSub.error
```

**Solid**
```tsx
import { useAll, useDb } from "jazz-tools/solid";
import { createSignal } from "solid-js";

const [status, setStatus] = createSignal<"open" | "done" | undefined>("open");
const db = useDb();
const todos = useAll(() => app.todos.where({ done: status() === "done" }));
```

In both, do not build the query once and reuse it; use the function/accessor form so changes re-subscribe.

Use a batch for independent local-first UI updates where each operation can apply immediately and optimistically together.

```ts
db.batch((b) => {
  b.insert(app.items, { name: "A" });
  b.insert(app.items, { name: "B" });
}).wait({ tier: "edge" }); // optional, if you want explicit durability
```

Use a transaction when writes must be staged until authority accepts and become visible atomically, globally consistent together.

```ts
await (await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.insert(app.items, { name: "A" });
  tx.update(app.items, idB, { name: "B" });
})).wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Initial schema with self-reference:

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  employees: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
    managerId: s.ref("employees").optional(),
  }),
};

export const app: s.App<s.Schema<typeof schema>> = s.defineApp(schema);
```

`managerId` is optional so top-level employees can have no manager. Jazz derives `manager` and a reverse `employeesViaManager` relation automatically.

Use these column types:

```ts
const schema = {
  events: s.table({
    occurredAt: s.date(),                 // event timestamp
    fingerprint: s.binary(),               // small binary payload
    projectId: s.ref("projects"),        // relation to projects
  }),
};
```

Keeping `fingerprint` as a normal scalar field means it is included in ordinary reads by default; no special eager-load API is needed (only explicit `select(...)` can exclude it).

Use `jazz-expo` only. 1) Treat this as a native build: add direct deps `jazz-tools`, `jazz-rn`, `expo-crypto`, `expo-secure-store`, `metro-runtime` and run dev builds (not Expo Go). 2) In the entry file, import polyfills before anything else that can load Jazz.
```ts
import "jazz-tools/expo/polyfills";
import registerRootComponent from "expo/src/launch/registerRootComponent";
import App from "./App";
registerRootComponent(App);
```
3) In Metro config, add `withJazz` so codegen/dev helpers are wired: keep existing Babel/Metro setup and only add what is required by your exact `expo`/`jazz-rn` versions.
4) Use React Native provider bindings and native auth helpers only:
```tsx
import { JazzProvider } from "jazz-tools/react-native";
import { useLocalFirstAuth } from "jazz-tools/expo";

export default function AppRoot() {
  const { secret, state } = useLocalFirstAuth();
  const config = useMemo(
    () => ({
      appId,
      serverUrl,
      env: "dev" as const,
      userBranch: "main",
      secret,
      dataPath,
    }),
    [secret, dataPath],
  );

  if (state !== "ready") return <Splash />;
  return <JazzProvider config={config}>{/* app */}</JazzProvider>;
}
```
5) Keep provider config stable and avoid creating a new identity during render. If identity is not ready, render fallback UI and do not mount the provider yet.
6) Verify by prebuilding both platforms and running `expo run:ios` and `expo run:android` so `jazz-rn` is actually linked in native projects.

Use `jazz-expo` only.

- Client ownership: the `JazzProvider` owns and disposes its client. Treat its `config` as immutable across renders and avoid recreating it every render. If you create a client manually, call `shutdown()` when your owning component unmounts; do not manually shut down a provider-owned client.
- Reactive query inputs: pass query inputs from React state directly and let undefined represent "not ready/skip". Keep identity and filter gating at the query boundary.
```tsx
const teamId = selectedTeamId;
const team = teamId ? useGet(db.teams, teamId) : undefined;
const tasks = useAll(team ? team.tasks : undefined);
```
`undefined` means loading/skipped query input; `[]` means an intentionally empty completed result.

- Background expectations: assume foreground-only sync unless you have implemented and tested a native background execution strategy for iOS/Android. Expect process suspension to pause live sync; after resume, validate reconciliation and settlement of queued writes.

To guarantee completion before success:

1. Upload with edge-tier write commitment:
```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });
const upload = await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label: "Profile photo",
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```
(Use `createFileFromStream` for streams.)

2. Handle download when local data is incomplete:
```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "local" });
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof FileNotFoundError) {
    // file row not visible yet/never visible
  }
  if (err instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) {
    // local cache has partial/inconsistent chunks
    const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  }
}
```

Treat `IncompleteFileDataError` (invalid-file-record / missing-part / part-size-mismatch) as an explicit recovery state and refetch from stronger tier; do not assume local partial data is valid for success.

Delete in dependency order while permissions still inherit from the parent:

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Never delete the parent first, because inherited `files`/`file_parts` delete rights may disappear before cleanup completes. This keeps cleanup authorised and avoids orphaning chunks.

Use the public Rust query surface as dynamic, then project to a strict typed layer.

1. Define one projection + decoder per query shape.
```rust
#[derive(Debug)]
struct TodoRow { id: ObjectId, title: String, done: bool, description: Option<String> }

fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, vals: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
    if vals.len() != 3 { return Err(AppError::ProjectionMismatch(vals.len())); }
    let title = match &vals[0] { Value::Text(s) => s.clone(), _ => return Err(AppError::BadValue("title".into())) };
    let done = match vals[1] { Value::Boolean(b) => b, _ => return Err(AppError::BadValue("done".into())) };
    let description = match &vals[2] {
        Value::Null => None,
        Value::Text(s) => Some(s.clone()),
        _ => return Err(AppError::BadValue("description".into())),
    };
    Ok(TodoRow { id, title, done, description })
}
```

2. Keep query shape explicit and stable.
```rust
let qb = QueryBuilder::new("todos").select(["title", "done", "description"]).order_by("title", true);
let rows: Vec<(ObjectId, Vec<Value>)> = client.query(qb).await?;
let typed: Vec<TodoRow> = rows
    .into_iter()
    .map(|(id, vals)| decode_todo(id, &vals))
    .collect::<Result<_, _>>()?;
```

3. Writes stay raw values, typed at service layer.
```rust
let (_id, _vals, batch_id) = client.insert("todos", row_input!("title"=>"Ship", "done"=>false, "description"=>Value::Null))?;
client.wait_for_batch(batch_id, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer).await?;
```

4. For updates/deletes use `row_input!` only for inserts and centralise all persistence effects behind typed repositories (`TodoRepo::list`, `TodoRepo::update_done`) so handler code never manipulates raw `Value` directly.

5. If schema drifts, decoder fails fast (length/variant/nullability checks) instead of silently remapping.

Use an explicit request boundary with one process-wide client and per-request session scoping.

1. Application state:
- build `AppContext` once
- create one `JazzClient::connect(context)` for the process
- keep the service/backend credential only on this root client

2. Per request:
- authenticate bearer/JWT to a trusted `Session`
- create `let db = app_state.jazz.for_session(session)`
- run both read and write through `db`
- never use admin/builder credential to perform caller writes

3. Handler pattern (Axum-style):
```rust
pub async fn complete_todo(
  State(state): State<AppState>,
  auth: CallerSession,
  Path(todo_id): Path<String>,
  Json(payload): Json<CompleteTodo>,
) -> Result<Json<TodoRow>, ServiceError> {
  let db = state.jazz.for_session(auth.session());

  let updates = vec![("done".into(), Value::Boolean(payload.done))];
  let id = ObjectId::from_str(&todo_id)?;
  let batch = db.update(id, updates)?;

  let timeout = std::time::Duration::from_secs(3);
  tokio::time::timeout(timeout, db.wait_for_batch(batch, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer))
      .await
      .map_err(|_| ServiceError::Timeout)??;

  let rows = wait_for_query(||
      db.query(QueryBuilder::new("todos").select(["title", "done"]).filter_id(id))
  ).await?;

  let row = rows.first().map(|(id, vals)| decode_todo(*id, vals)).transpose()?;
  row.ok_or(ServiceError::NotFound)
}
```

4. Return responses with clear status mapping:
- 401 unauthenticated
- 403 policy/authorship denied
- 404 row absent or policy-filtered
- 503/504 durability timeout or disconnection
- 500 for decoder/schema internal failures only

5. Choose durability tier by contract: `EdgeServer` for user feedback, `GlobalServer` when authoritative visibility matters (admin dashboards, finance/consistency-sensitive flows). Always bounded-time wait around waits.

Use a local server + two clients, persist writes with edge-tier waits, and compare query results as an unordered set.

```ts
import { afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it, vi } from "vitest";
import { createDb } from "jazz-tools";
import { deploy, startLocalJazzServer } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { app } from "../schema";
import permissions from "../permissions";

let server: any;
let alice: any;
let bob: any;

beforeEach(async () => {
  server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
  await deploy({
    serverUrl: server.url,
    appId: server.appId,
    adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
    schema: app,
    permissions,
  });

  alice = await createDb({
    appId: server.appId,
    serverUrl: server.url,
    adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
    driver: { type: "memory" },
  });

  bob = await createDb({
    appId: server.appId,
    serverUrl: server.url,
    adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
    driver: { type: "memory" },
  });
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await alice?.shutdown();
  await bob?.shutdown();
  await server?.stop();
});

describe("sync order stability", () => {
  it("syncs all rows to the second client independent of row order", async () => {
    const created = await Promise.all([
      alice.insert(app.notes, { title: "Second" }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      alice.insert(app.notes, { title: "First" }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      alice.insert(app.notes, { title: "Third" }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
    ]);

    const expected = created
      .map((row) => ({ id: row.id, title: row.title }))
      .sort((a, b) => a.id.localeCompare(b.id));

    await vi.waitFor(async () => {
      const remoteRows = await bob.all(app.notes, { tier: "edge" });
      const actual = remoteRows
        .map((row) => ({ id: row.id, title: row.title }))
        .sort((a, b) => a.id.localeCompare(b.id));

      expect(actual).toEqual(expected);
    });
  });
});
```

Why it is stable: assertion sorts by `id`, so you are testing convergence, not accidental result order.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` and scoped sessions for Alice/Bob; verify Bob cannot read the row (`[]`) and cannot write it (`expectDenied`).

```ts
import { afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it } from "vitest";
import { createPolicyTestApp, type PolicyTestApp } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import permissions from "../permissions";
import { app } from "../schema";

let testApp: PolicyTestApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

describe("row policy", () => {
  it("denies Bob read and write access to Alice's row", async () => {
    const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
    const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });

    const note = alice.insert(app.notes, { title: "Alice-only" }).value;

    await expect(bob.all(app.notes.where({ id: note.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);

    bob.expectDenied((db) => db.update(app.notes, note.id, { title: "Bob edit" }));

    // Optional second write-check if delete should also be denied
    // bob.expectDenied((db) => db.delete(app.notes, note.id));

    await expect(alice.all(app.notes.where({ id: note.id }))).resolves.toHaveLength(1);
  });
});
```

Keep reads and writes separate and ensure read assertions expect an empty result rather than an exception.
